{{pp-semi-sock|small=yes}} [[Image:Giza-pyramids.JPG|thumb|300px|From north to south: parts of the city of Giza, the Giza Necropolis, and part of the Giza plateau]] The '''Giza Plateau''' ({{lang-ar|جيزة بلاتي}}) is a [[plateau]] that is located in [[Giza]], [[Egypt]]. The famous [[Giza Necropolis]] is located in this geographical area, which is characterized by a sandy, [[desert]] [[climate]] and [[terrain]] with little [[vegetation]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hopkins|first1=Daniel J.|title=Merriam-Webster's Geographical Dictionary|date=1997|publisher=Merriam Webster|isbn=978-0877795469|edition=3rd}}</ref> "The general elevation is just over 3,000 ft above sea level but the highest points on it rise to 5,077 and 4,293."<ref>{{cite book|title=The Ibis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ML5HAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA206|volume=2|year=1906|publisher=British Ornithologists' Union (United Kingdom)|pages=206–}}</ref>
==Ancient findings== The plateau has many tombs. One of the people working on clearing the sands from around the Great Sphinx was [[Eugène Grébaut]], a French Director of the [[Supreme Council of Antiquities|Antiquities Service]]<ref name="SCAHistory">{{cite web|title=A Brief History of the Supreme Council of Antiquities (SCA): 1858 to present|url=http://www.sca-egypt.org/eng/sca_history.htm|website=SCA – Egypt|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161017043511/http://www.sca-egypt.org/eng/SCA_History.htm|archivedate=2016-10-17|df=}}</ref> "In the beginning of the year 1887, the chest, the paws, the altar, and plateau were all made visible. Flights of steps were unearthed, and finally accurate measurements were taken of the great figures. The height from the lowest of the steps was found to be one hundred feet, and the space between the paws was found to be thirty-five feet long and ten feet wide. Here there was formerly an altar; and a stele of [[Thutmose IV]] was discovered, recording a dream in which he was ordered to clear away the sand that even then was gathering round the site of the Sphinx."<ref name="HistoryofEgypt">{{cite book|last1=Rappoport|first1=S.|title=The Project Gutenberg EBook of History Of Egypt From 330 B.C. To The Present Time, Volume 12 (of 12), by S. Rappoport|publisher=The Grolier Society Publishers, London|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/17332/17332-h/17332-h.htm|accessdate=31 October 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304095932/http://www.gutenberg.org/files/17332/17332-h/17332-h.htm|archivedate=4 March 2016|df=}}</ref>
==Modern history== Modern Giza's layout is accessed by two main roads.<ref name="LonelyPlanet">{{cite book|last1=Firestone|first1=Matthew|title=Egypt|date=2010|publisher=The Lonely Planet|isbn=9781742203324|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tU7KBLLxRx8C&pg=PA145&dq=giza+plateau,+tourist&hl=es&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwivyYjj0obQAhXL4iYKHS87C2EQ6AEIJjAB#v=onepage&q=giza%20plateau%2C%20tourist&f=false|accessdate=1 November 2016}}</ref> The first from the north leads to [[Khufu|Khufu's]] pyramids and the other road leads near the [[Great Sphinx of Giza|Sphinx's]] front court, from the east. They cross the [[Nile River]] from the east bank and follow the causeway westward. Dominating the plateau and running in a southwest diagonal through the site are the three pyramids of the [[Pharaoh|pharaohs]] Khufu, [[Khafra]], and [[Menkaura]]. The northernmost, and the largest, one belongs to Khufu. Khafra's pyramid is built precisely on a southwest diagonal to his father's pyramid, as well as having been built on higher ground to create the illusion of being bigger. The pyramid of Menkaura is much smaller and is not aligned along the same diagonal line as the other two pyramids.<ref>{{cite book|title=Egypt, Land and lives of the pharaohs revealed|publisher=Global Book Publishing|isbn=1 74048 056 2|pages=126}}</ref> On a clear day the Pyramids of [[Abusir]] can be seen from the Giza Plateau.<ref name="TravelersGuide" /> It is a place attractive to tourists, researchers and adherents of [[New Age]].<ref name="Womb">{{cite book|last1=Prakasha|first1=Anaiya Aon|last2=Prakasha|first2=Padma Aon|title=Womb Wisdom: Awakening the Creative and Forgotten Powers of the Feminine|date=2011|publisher=Inner Traditions / Bear & Co,|isbn=9781594778247|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ldSIzzNlIooC&printsec=frontcover&dq=giza+plateau&hl=es&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjcn5CSpYbQAhUC7CYKHfckAjw4WhDoAQgjMAE#v=onepage&q=giza%20plateau&f=false|accessdate=1 November 2016}}</ref><ref name="NewAge2">{{cite book|last1=Malkowski|first1=Edward F.|title=Return of the Golden Age: Ancient History and the Key to Our Collective Future|date=2013|publisher=Inner Traditions / Bear & Co,|isbn=9781620551981|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yHJnAwAAQBAJ&dq=giza+plateau,+barren&source=gbs_navlinks_s|accessdate=1 November 2016}}</ref> Stout shoes or jogging shoes are recommended for visitors to the plateau.<ref name="TravelersGuide">{{cite book|last1=West|first1=John Anthony|title=The Traveler's Key to Ancient Egypt: A Guide to the Sacred Places of Ancient Egypt (pg 150)|date=1995|publisher=Quest Books|isbn=9780835607247|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EG0BzbCu0m4C&pg=PA85&dq=giza+plateau&hl=es&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiAncCzoIbQAhWMNSYKHTg1CzQQ6AEIKzAC#v=onepage&q=giza%20plateau&f=false|accessdate=1 November 2016}}</ref>
The plateau has been a favorite venue for squash tournaments for many years, with a break between 2007 and 2016.<ref name="squash venue">{{cite web|title=Squash Returns To Great Pyramid of Giza|url=http://www.worldsquash.org/ws/news/28263|website=worldsquash.org|accessdate=26 May 2018|language=English|date=29 June 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170306164256/http://www.worldsquash.org/ws/news/28263|archivedate=6 March 2017|df=}}</ref><ref name="BBC 2006">{{cite news|title=World Open squash returns to Giza|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/squash/4922598.stm|accessdate=26 May 2018|work=BBC|date=19 April 2006|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608012944/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/squash/4922598.stm|archivedate=8 June 2012|df=}}</ref>
Some looting took place there during the [[2011 Egyptian revolution|Egyptian Revolution of 2011]].<ref>{{cite news | last =Hartley | first =Aiden | title =The new tomb raiders | newspaper =[[The Spectator]] | location =UK | date =9 November 2013 | url =http://www.spectator.co.uk/features/9073351/the-new-tomb-raiders/ | accessdate =10 November 2013 | deadurl =no | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20131110104838/http://www.spectator.co.uk/features/9073351/the-new-tomb-raiders/ | archivedate =10 November 2013 | df = }}</ref>
==Grand Egyptian Museum== Plans to build the [[Grand Egyptian Museum]] (GEM), on the Giza Plateau were stalled and began again. Initially hopes were to have the GEM completed by 2012.<ref name="GEM2012">{{cite news |last1=Bradley |first1=M. |title=Grand Egyptian Museum project moves forward |url=http://www.thenational.ae/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20090820/FOREIGN/708199898/1185/enewsletter |accessdate=1 November 2016 |agency=The National |date=August 20, 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090925012540/http://www.thenational.ae/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20090820%2FFOREIGN%2F708199898%2F1185%2Fenewsletter |archivedate=25 September 2009 |df= }}</ref> In October, 2015, the Minister of Antiquities, [[Mamdouh Eldamaty]], stated that GEM will be inaugurated in 2018.<ref name="GEM">{{cite news|last1=Al-Youm|first1=Al-Masry|title=Great Museum to be inaugurated in May 2018|url=http://www.egyptindependent.com/news/great-museum-be-inaugurated-may-2018|accessdate=1 November 2016|agency=Egypt Independent|date=October 5, 2015|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227043441/http://www.egyptindependent.com/news/great-museum-be-inaugurated-may-2018|archivedate=27 December 2016|df=}}</ref>
