{{copyedit|date=November 2018}} '''Place names in India''' are usually in Indian languages. However, a good number of place names are from European languages such as Portuguese, Dutch, English as well as Arabic.
==Common place names== Most place names are named after the prominent geographical entity nearby such as river, lake. Some place names are named after popular personalities such as Kings as well as Mythological characters. Good number of place names are based on Hindu mythology, while a handful names are based on Islamic as well as christianic influence.
==Anglicised Names== Some anglicised names have been officially changed to reflect native spellings. The names of the cities, towns and villages are usually in Indian languages, while most street names carry English names. Example : [[Washermanpet]], [[George Town, Chennai]]
==Variations== Certain names have variations in different languages. Oor/ooru is a common dravidian name which means a place, is called as oor in Tamil and Malayalam, whereas it is called as ooru in Telugu and Kannada.
===Andhra Pradesh=== Common suffixes are ooru, palli, pudi, pedu, peta, patnam, wada, cherla, seema etc. Example: [[Guntur]], [[Chintalapudi, West Godavari district|Chintalapudi]], [[Yerpedu]], [[Chilakaluripet]], [[Visakhapatnam]], [[Vijayawada]], [[Macherla]] etc.
===Arunachal Pradesh=== {{Empty section|date=December 2015}}
===Bihar=== {{Empty section|date=December 2015}}
===Chhattisgarh=== {{Empty section|date=December 2015}}
===Delhi=== {{Empty section|date=December 2015}}
===Goa=== {{Empty section|date=December 2015}}
===Jammu and Kashmir=== {{Empty section|date=December 2015}}
===Jharkhand=== {{Empty section|date=December 2015}}
===Karnataka=== Common endings are ooru, palaya, halli, pete, seeme. Prefix like Sri are also found, but in lesser number.
{|class="wikitable" ! Suffix !! meaning !! Common place names |- | Bhavi || || Arabhavi, Sulibhavi, Bilebhavi, Nagarbhavi |- | Gud || || Nanjangud, Handigud |- | Halli || || Kaladevanahalli, |- | Keri || || Madikeri, Tallikeri, |- | Kote || || Bagalakote, |- | Ooru/uru || || Bengaluru, Mysuru, Mangaluru, Chikkamagaluru, Kitturu. Emmiganuru, |- | Pete || || Chikkupete, Hosapete |- | Pura || || Kundapura, Narasimharajapura, Kanakapura |}
===Kerala=== In Kerala, most names are based on dravidian rootwords just as in Tamil Nadu. Common suffixes include oor, cheri/sheri, kulam, kaadu, Naadu and mangalam. Examples: [[Kadavoor]], [[Puthusherry]], [[Kuttanad]], [[kunnamangalam]]
===Maharashtra=== {{Empty section|date=December 2015}}
===Manipur=== {{Empty section|date=December 2015}}
===Mizoram=== {{Empty section|date=December 2015}}
===Orissa=== {{Empty section|date=December 2015}}
===Tamil Nadu=== In Tamil Nadu, common suffixes are oor, puram, kudi, cheri, paakkam, pattinam, palayam, kaadu, pettai, mangalam, seemai and kuppam. Common prefix is thiru. Majority of the names are in Tamil language. While place names in Telugu or Kannada can be seen in border areas and Sanskrit names are also found because of the historical relationship of Sanskrit with hinduism. {|class = "wikitable" ! Suffix !! Meaning !! Common Place names |- | Oor/ur || || [[Ambattur]], [[Thanjavur]], [[Karur]], |- | Kaadu || Forest || [[Yercaud]], |- | pattinam || Coastal area || [[Nagapattinam]] |- | puram || || |}
===Tripura=== Common suffix include mura. {|class="wikitable" ! suffix !! meaning !! common places |- | assa || || Ambassa, Bagbassa |- | bari || || Churaibari, Jolaibari |- | chhara || ||Laxmanchhara, Nabinchhara, Karaichhara, Bagaichhara, Dhanichhara, Sanichhara |- | mura || || Teliamura, Sonamura, |}
===West Bengal===
==Anglicised Names== Some anglicised names have been officially changed to reflect native spellings. The names of the cities, towns and villages are usually in Indian languages, while most street names carry English names. Example : [[Washermanpet]], [[George Town, Chennai]]
==Places with multiple names== Some cities have different names in different languages. *Mangalore: Kudla, Mangalapuram, Kodial
